@startuml fig-binary-proto-tcp-framing
skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

title Binary Protocol over TCP — LEN_BYTE + Pickle Framing

participant "Client\n(interactive prompt)" as C #FFE0B2
participant "Server\n127.0.0.1:3333" as S #C8E6C9

C -> S : TCP connect

== Binary Request/Response ==

note over C
  User types: add user1 Alice
  Client builds:
    Request(cmd="add",
      key="user1", resource="Alice")
  pickle.dump -> bytes
  Prepend LEN_BYTE (1 byte)
end note

C -[#1565C0]> S : [LEN_BYTE] [pickled Request]
note right of S
  Read data[0] = message_length
  Read remaining bytes
  pickle.load -> Request object
  Execute: state.add("user1","Alice")
  Build: Response("user1 added")
  pickle.dump + LEN_BYTE
end note
S -[#43A047]-> C : [LEN_BYTE] [pickled Response]

note over C
  pickle.load -> Response
  Display: response.payload
end note

== keys Command ==

C -[#1565C0]> S : [LEN_BYTE] [pickled Request(cmd="keys")]
S -[#43A047]-> C : [LEN_BYTE] [pickled Response("user1")]

== Termination ==

C -> S : exit (client closes socket)

legend right
  Each message is prefixed with a single byte
  indicating total message length (max 255 B).
  Payload is serialised with Python pickle.
  Not human-readable in Wireshark — appears
  as a binary blob in the TCP stream.
endlegend
@enduml
